SET biography = E'Founded in 2012 by Gabriel Hendifar and Jeremy Anderson, Apparatus is a New York-based interdisciplinary design studio that has redefined the relationship between lighting, furniture, and the environments they inhabit. Guided by the modernist principle of Gesamtkunstwerk — the total work of art — the studio creates fully articulated collections in which individual pieces function as artefacts of a holistic world, each summoned by a singular creative vision.\n\nhttps://s30964.p1087.sites.pressdns.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/APPARATUS-PORTRAIT-2.jpg | Gabriel Hendifar & Jeremy Anderson — Photo: Wichmann + Bendtsen\n\nThe Apparatus origin story begins not in a workshop but in a Los Angeles apartment. In 2010, Hendifar — who had studied costume and scenic design at UCLA and was working in fashion and interior design — and Anderson, then a public relations professional and avid ceramicist, moved in together and found themselves unable to afford the kind of lighting they wanted. \u2018Jeremy has always been a tinkerer,\u2019 Hendifar told Surface Magazine. \u2018I\u2019d been designing interiors and making womenswear. We made some lights.\u2019\n\nhttps://s30964.pcdn.co/introspective-magazine/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/APPARATUS_SALONE2017_04.jpg | Milan Showroom — Lantern & Portal Dining Table — Photo: Paola Pansini\n\nOne evening, Sven Neumann, owner of L.A.\u2019s Gallery L7, came for dinner. Struck by the handmade fixtures, he began selling them on consignment. Design blogs took notice. Among the earliest commissions was an order for three Compass fixtures from a restaurant in Shanghai — a project the pair accepted despite having no idea how to wire for 240-volt electricity.\n\n\u2018We just said yes and figured things out,\u2019 Hendifar recalled. When Anderson\u2019s career relocated the couple to New York, they rented a 200-square-foot studio and formally launched their first collection at the International Contemporary Furniture Fair (ICFF) in 2012.\n\nhttps://youtu.be/krWUk3Dm2-Q | Apparatus Studio Visit — Surface Magazine\n\n<strong>The Art of Seduction: Materials & Philosophy</strong>\n\n\u2018I learned how to make things by putting them on my body,\u2019 Hendifar has said of his fashion training. \u2018That moment when you put something on and decide you have to have it — that electric moment where a thing becomes a feeling — that\u2019s what we really strive to capture. The way to do that is through seduction, and the way we seduce is through materials.\u2019\n\nhttps://images.surfacemag.com/app/uploads/2018/08/06174805/Apparatus_Stills_Print-10-2000x1334.jpg | Workshop — Photo: Kelsey Allen / Surface Magazine\n\nAt Apparatus, hand-patinated brass forms the structural backbone of nearly every piece. It is combined with sensual, time-honoured materials — marble, suede, horsehair, lacquer, porcelain, alabaster, hand-frosted mouth-blown glass, and hand-cast resin — all fabricated with a devotion to small-studio craftsmanship. Each piece embodies a deft balance between mechanisation and the handmade. The studio\u2019s custom component catalogue now numbers more than 700 parts. \u2018We want to be making things that people are going to be collecting and trying to find a hundred years from now,\u2019 Hendifar told 1stDibs.\n\nhttps://apparatusstudio.com/cdn/shop/files/APPARATUS_ABOUT_05.jpg?v=1761232246&width=3000 | Hand carving detail — Photo: Apparatus Studio\n\n<strong>Collections as \u2018Acts\u2019: Narrative Design</strong>\n\nApparatus organises its output not as conventional collections but as \u2018Acts\u2019 — theatrical chapters that reference specific temporal, cultural, and historical touchstones. Act I launched at the Chelsea showroom with the Tassel and Circuit fixture series, channelling Art Deco through a late-1970s lens. Act II drew from the Vienna Secession, Eileen Gray, and Pierre Chareau, introducing the now-iconic Lantern lamps in slip-cast porcelain and brass.\n\nhttps://media.architecturaldigest.com/photos/57a2085da065cffc07e866c8/master/w_1600,c_limit/0916-apparatus-lighting-4.jpg | Chelsea Showroom — Cloud Pendants constellation — Photo: Architectural Digest\n\nAct III became Apparatus\u2019s most deeply personal collection. For the first time, Hendifar mined his own cultural heritage — his Iranian roots — to inform the work. The genesis was a wooden box, intricately inlaid in the Persian Khatam style, which his grandmother had carried out of Iran in 1979 as a political refugee. As a first-generation American born after the Islamic Revolution, Hendifar sought to reconcile inherited memories with contemporary identity. The collection included a textile collaboration with the historic French maison Pierre Frey, translating Persian marquetry techniques into fabric.\n\nhttps://estliving.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/est-living-apparatus-studio-interview-isafahan-collection-1.webp | ISFAHAN textile collaboration with Pierre Frey — Photo: est living\n\n<strong>From 200 Square Feet to a Global Footprint</strong>\n\nThe studio has moved through five spaces in its history, each larger than the last — from a 200-square-foot New York studio in 2012, to a Milan showroom in 2015, to a 10,000-square-foot headquarters at 124 West 30th Street in Chelsea in 2016, combining workshop, showroom, and offices in a former school building. In 2021, a purpose-built factory opened in Red Hook, Brooklyn, enabling the Manhattan space to be reimagined as a communal creative hub.\n\nhttps://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod/images/edc050122apparatusstudio-004-1649692202.jpg | 2022 Studio reimagination — Photo: Stephen Kent Johnson / Elle Decor\n\nIn May 2023, Apparatus opened its first European gallery on Mount Street in Mayfair, London — a 3,200-square-foot Grade II-listed building dating to the 1890s, conceived as a living expression of the brand\u2019s immersive design ethos. Today Apparatus employs approximately 110 team members across design, sales, operations, and manufacturing, with showrooms in New York, Los Angeles, Milan, and London.\n\nhttps://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/eQwK4YEcx555DzQvFNj2yY.jpg | London Gallery, Mount Street, Mayfair — Photo: Matthew Placek / Wallpaper*\n\nThe studio has created environments for the Four Seasons, Soho House, Paris\u2019s Hôtel Lutetia, and architect Annabelle Selldorf. Interior designers Jamie Drake, Kelly Behun, Christine Gachot, and Nate Berkus are among its most prominent advocates. Gabriel Hendifar serves as Artistic Director and CEO; Jeremy Anderson, co-founder, initially handled operations, production, and finishing — personally wiring fixtures, applying patinas, and hand-finishing leather details in the early years.',
